"The Warriors' Home and Away Gap"

By: Eric Youmans, Nebil Ozer, Nadula Kadawedduwa

Introduction

Coming into the 2022-2023 season the Golden State Warriors were the defending champions. They finished the 2021-2022 regular season as the 3rd seed in the Western Confrence and they managed to exceed most expectations by making a championship run in the playoffs.

While there are more factors, one would expect the defending champions to be one of the better teams in the NBA. However, the Warriors this regular season (2022-2023) finished only slightly above a 50% winning rate. Variance between seasons is not uncommon but there is something especially intresting about the Warrior this season. They have one of the best home records in the league, but one of the worst road records, despite this season having one of the highest home-road splits in NBA history (https://sircharlesincharge.com/2023/01/13/nba-road-splits-staggering/)

Our goal is to find out why this happened, and where the Golden State Warriors need to improve in their "on the road" games if they hope to do better next season. First we will import our data and prepare it for use. Then we will visualize the gap, then we will explore similarities between the Warriors and teams with the best/worst home/df records. Then we will attempt to use these stats to make a predicitive model on a teams home/road record.

Image from: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Golden_State_Warriors_logo.svg

Throughout this analysis, we made use of the data collected in the following two pages, readily available as CSV files:

https://www.nbastuffer.com/2022-2023-nba-team-stats/

https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_2023.html#all_confs_standings_E

Due to the NBA having very well-documented statistics and a wealth of data to choose from, we were able to obtain our data very easily.

Visualization and Showcasing the Problem¶

Below we visualized the Teams with the most and least wins in Total, At Home and lastly on the Road.

Total Win %¶

We found that Golden State's total WP (Win Percentage) is 53.7%, their home WP is 80.5% (The third highest in the NBA), and their road WP is 26.8% (The fourth lowest in the NBA). The teams with the highest total WP include Milwaukee, Boston, Philadephia, Denver, Clevland, and Memphis, and they have been marked as Green on all four plots. The teams with the lowest total WP include Charlotte, Houston, San Antonio, and Detroit, which have been marked with Red on all four plots.

Home Win %¶

The teams with the highest Home WP are Memphis, Denver, Golden State, Boston, Milwaukee, Clevland, and Philadelphia. All of these teams are also included in the teams with the total WP besides Golden State. The teams with the lowest home WP include Houston, San Antonio, Charlotte, and Detroi. These are the same exact teams that also had the lowest total WP. The teams with the highest road % include Milwaukee, Boston, Sacramento, and Philadephia.

Road Win %¶

The teams with the lowest road% include Golden State, Houston, San Antonio, and Detroit. We can see from these charts how odd it is that Golden State has such a difference between their home and road WP. Most of the teams with high total win%'s also have high total win%'s and high total road %'s. Most of the teams with low total win%'s are the same teams with low home and road wins. However, Golden State is a clear outlier in this trend.

def assign_color(row):
    if row['TEAM'] == 'Golden State':
        return 'yellow'  # Golden State Warriors
    elif row['>60%']:
        return 'green'  # Top teams
    elif row['<40%']:
        return 'red'  # Bottom teams
    else:
        return 'grey'  # All other teams

df = df.sort_values(by=['WIN%'], ascending=False)
df['>60%'] = df['WIN%'] >= 0.6
df['<40%'] = df['WIN%'] <= 0.4
my_palette = df.apply(assign_color, axis=1)
plot = sns.barplot(data=df, x='TEAM', y='WIN%', palette=my_palette)
plt.gcf().set_size_inches(14,4)
plt.title('Total Win %')
plot.set_xticklabels(plot.get_xticklabels(), rotation=30, ha='right')

Conclusions:¶

Looking at the graphs above, we can clearly see that there is some sort of discrepancy going on with Golden State's WP, with Memphis having a quite similar record but not as exaggerated, sitting well over 10% above Golden State in their Road WP.

Now, although there is a visible split in the Golden State Warriors' WP, some actual numbers indicating that there is something going on would be better. Below, we find the top 5 z-scores of each team's home road diff, essentially just a measurement of how far away a team is from the average home/road split. In our dataframe, GSW is the 19th row, and can be seen to have a z-score of 2.7, with Memphis (16) trailing at 2.19. With a z-score of 2.72, GSW's home/road split is far from the average, indicating pretty definitively that GSW are very unbalanced in their win and loss percentages. Despite Memphis also having a high z-score, GSW is far more extreme than them, an outlier amongst outliers, if you will.

However, our purpose with this analysis does not end at figuring out that there is a discrepancy. That much is pretty clear to see just from the scorelines. We want to figure out why the Golden State Warriors have such a discrepancy. Thus, our next steps involve finding the source of this discrepancy, and pinpointing what it is that the Golden State Warriors do right at home but not on the road that causes this gap.

home_max = home.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).max()
home_min = home.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).min()

road_max = road.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).max()
road_min = road.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).min()

standard_home = GS_num_home.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).apply(lambda x: (x - home_min[x.index])/
(home_max[x.index] - home_min[x.index]), axis=1)

standard_road = GS_num_road.drop(['RANK', 'TEAM', 'CONF', 'DIVISION', 'GP'], axis=1).apply(lambda x: (x - road_min[x.index])/
(road_max[x.index] - road_min[x.index]), axis=1)

    ax.scatter(df[df['TEAM'] == team]['oPPG'], df[df['TEAM'] == team]['WIN%'])
